howing how many choose to comply with—rather than resist—social norms in their pursuit of status and belonging.Coming of Age in Iran tells the unprecedented story of how Iran’s young and struggling attempt to extend dignity and alleviate misery, illuminating the promises—and limits—of finding one’s place during a time of profound uncertainty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aPoor youthzIran. 0aPovertyzIran. 0aYouthzIranxEconomic conditions. 0aYouthzIranxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAccentuated Conformism.  aAgency.  aAppearances.  aAspirations.  aBodily Capital.  aCultural Mimicry.  aCultural Production.  aCulture.  aDignity.  aDrug Use.  aEmbourgeoisement.  aFace Game.  aFace Rules.  aFace.  aFamily Support.  aFeminization of Work.  aHard Work.  aHegemony.  aHorizontal Exchange Networks.  aIncremental Mobility.  aInequality.  aInformal Work.  aKelās.  aMasculinity.  aMoral Capital.  aMoral Pollution.  aMoral Purity.  aMoral Self.  aMorality.  aPre-Existing Resources.  aResistance.  aRisk-Taking.  aRitual Action.  aSari.  aSatellite Television.  aSelf Sufficiency.  aSexual Cleanliness.  aSocial Capital.  aSocial Media.  aSocial Mobility.  aSocial Ties.  aSocioeconomic Mobility.  aStatus.  aStreet Smarts.  aSymbolic Boundaries.  aTastemaking.  aTehran.  aThe Gaze.  aVertical Exchange Networks.  aYouth.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479862085.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479862085423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479862085/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles